text: Awwww man! HUD's for cars is like one of my dreams.
I tried prototyping one w/ an iPod (first gen) back in 2004. We'd figured out an approach that would take its signal and display it on polarized film.
we spliced an old dock cable
anyways
:P his license plate number is SANDWCH
<@U026NB2U2>: That's pretty sweet. I had an idea I was tossing around with some friends at school that was a similar approach (sans iPod)

This seems rad for things like mapping data or obstacle detection, but i question if we need to display text message or (eventually) movies up there. i guess it's better than people texting on their phone, but still non-optimal in my mind.
Most optimal would be that my car does the driving for me, and I can just relax, in my opinion.
i had one in my loaner the other day (fully integrated) it was amazing
keeps your eyes on the road
You didn't find it distracting / drawing focus away from what was actually happening? If that's the case, then I'd be fully behind it.

i think visual information/interface in a car draws attention away from the activity of driving attentively. there was that research that showed having another person talking to you in the car was as bad as texting for diminishing response times etc. so while looking away from the road is clearly bad, its taking your brain off the wheel, as it were, that's the real problem.
I'd like to see research about other people in the car providing stimuli that make it harder for the driver to doze off
there must be a grey area between asleep and distracted
I still think the technology is cool and can have some applicability in ways that promote good driving. Highlighting anomalies in the road ahead, or pedestrians crossing would be good examples.

It's also worth noting that the solution doesn't have to be ideal... heads up texting isn't as good as no texting. But, in the absence of heads up texting, people aren't defaulting to no texting; they're defaulting to texting on their phones. Given that reality, heads up texting is an improvement.
